Let's think step by step. Hint 2 tells us that the constant term of $f(x)$ is equal to 66. The constant term of any polynomial is just its constant coefficient, namely $a_0=66$. Therefore, when evaluating the product of the roots of $f(x)$ as described in Hint 1, we must have $a_0=r_1r_2\dotsm r_n$. Given that $a_n=2$, $a_0=66$ and that the product of the roots of the polynomial is $1$, as calculated in Hint 1, we get \begin{align*}
    r_1 r_2 \dotsm r_n &= 1\\
    r_1 r_2 \dotsm r_n & = 66\\
    \Rightarrow\qquad 66&=1\\
    \text{(no solution)}
    \end{align*}

This clearly indicates that we must have more than one root in order for the product of the roots of the polynomial to be equal to 66.

But there's another important piece of information here that I missed earlier - this product is equal to $(-1)^n(a_n/a_{n-1})$.
